                        "**High-level architecture** (p. 62): you need a counter per user/IP; if it exceeds the limit, disallow the request. Do not store counters in a **database** — disk access is too slow. Use an **in-memory cache**, which is fast and supports time-based expiration. Redis is the popular choice, offering two commands:\n"
                        "- **`INCR`** — increment the stored counter by 1.\n"
                        "- **`EXPIRE`** — set a timeout; when it expires, the counter is automatically deleted.\n"
                        "\n"
                        "Flow (pp. 62-63): client → rate-limiting middleware → fetch the counter from the matching bucket in Redis → if the limit is reached, reject; otherwise forward to the API servers, increment the counter, and save it back to Redis.\n"
                        "\n"
                        "**Rate-limiting rules** (p. 64): Lyft open-sourced theirs; rules are written in config files saved on disk. Example:\n"
                        "\n"
                        "```yaml\n"
                        "domain: messaging\n"
                        "descriptors:\n"
                        "  - key: message_type\n"
                        "    value: marketing\n"
                        "    rate_limit:\n"
                        "      unit: day\n"
                        "      requests_per_unit: 5\n"
                        "```\n"
                        "\n"
                        "This allows 5 marketing messages/day; another example caps logins at 5 per minute (p. 64).\n"
                        "\n"
                        "**Exceeding the limit** (p. 64): return **HTTP 429 (Too Many Requests)**; optionally enqueue rate-limited requests to process later (e.g., overflow orders). **Headers** tell the client its status:\n"
                        "- `X-Ratelimit-Remaining` — allowed requests left in the window.\n"
                        "- `X-Ratelimit-Limit` — calls allowed per window.\n"
                        "- `X-Ratelimit-Retry-After` — seconds to wait before retrying.\n"
                        "\n"
                        "A throttled user receives 429 plus `X-Ratelimit-Retry-After` (pp. 64-65). In the **detailed design** (p. 65), rules live on disk and workers periodically pull them into cache; the middleware loads rules from cache, fetches counters and the last-request timestamp from Redis, then forwards or returns 429 (request dropped or queued).\n"
                        "\n"
                        "**Distributed environment** raises two challenges (p. 66):\n"
                        "- **Race condition** — the steps are read counter, check `counter + 1 > threshold`, then increment. Under concurrency, two requests reading counter=3 before either writes both store 4, when the correct value is 5. Locks fix this but significantly slow the system; the recommended solutions are **Lua scripts** and Redis **sorted sets** (p. 66).\n"
                        "- **Synchronization** — one limiter server cannot handle millions of users. Because the web tier is stateless, a client may hit different limiters that do not share state. Avoid **sticky sessions** (not scalable or flexible); instead use a **centralized store like Redis** (pp. 66-67).\n"
                        "\n"
                        "**Performance and monitoring** (pp. 67-68): use a multi-data-center / edge setup to cut latency (Cloudflare had 194 edge servers as of 5/20/2020) and synchronize with an **eventual consistency** model. Monitor whether the algorithm and rules are effective; relax overly strict rules, and switch to the burst-friendly **token bucket** when traffic like flash sales defeats the current algorithm (p. 68).\n"
                        "\n"
                        "**Soft vs hard limits** (p. 69): a **hard** limit means requests can never exceed the threshold; a **soft** limit means requests may exceed it for a short period. You can also rate-limit at other OSI layers — e.g., by IP at layer 3 via Iptables, versus the application layer 7 (HTTP) covered here (p. 69)."
