                        "Keep these five in mind as the scoring rubric. In the high-level design step, the author evaluates four options against exactly this list, and three of them fail at least one requirement — which is precisely why the chapter lands on Twitter Snowflake. For example, \"ordered by date\" knocks out plain UUIDs and multi-master replication; \"numerical only\" and \"64-bit\" also knock out UUID; \"10,000/sec\" plus availability concerns weaken the single ticket server. The interview skill being tested is translating fuzzy requirements into concrete, testable constraints and then carrying those constraints through every design decision rather than reaching for a familiar tool."
