                        "**Approach 1 — Hash + collision resolution** (pp. 125-126). Hash the long URL with a well-known function (**CRC32, MD5, or SHA-1**). Problem: even the shortest output (CRC32) is **longer than 7 characters**. Fix:\n"
                        "1. Take the **first 7 characters** of the hash value.\n"
                        "2. Truncating causes **hash collisions**. Resolve them by **recursively appending a predefined string** to the input and re-hashing until no collision is found.\n"
                        "3. Checking the database for an existing `shortURL` on every request is expensive, so use a **bloom filter** — a \"space-efficient probabilistic technique to test if an element is a member of a set\" — to cheaply screen for likely collisions before querying.\n"
                        "\n"
                        "**Approach 2 — Base-62 conversion** (pp. 126-127). Convert a number into base 62 because there are 62 possible characters. The mapping is `0-0, ..., 9-9, 10-a, ..., 35-z, 36-A, ..., 61-Z` (so `a`=10, `Z`=61). Example, converting `11157` (base 10):\n"
                        "```\n"
                        "11157 = 2*62^2 + 55*62^1 + 59*62^0 = [2, 55, 59] -> [2, T, X]\n"
                        "```\n"
                        "so the short URL is `https://tinyurl.com/2TX` (p. 127).\n"
                        "\n"
                        "**Comparison** (Table 8-3, p. 127). Hash + collision resolution produces a **fixed-length** (7-char) output but requires **collision checks** on each new URL; base-62 conversion **avoids collisions** (each ID is unique) but its output **length is not fixed** — it grows with the ID — and it **depends on a unique ID generator**.\n"
                        "\n"
                        "**URL shortening deep dive** (pp. 127-129) — the design uses **base-62 conversion**:\n"
                        "1. `longURL` is the input.\n"
                        "2. Check if `longURL` is already in the database.\n"
                        "3. If yes, fetch and return the existing `shortURL`.\n"
                        "4. If new, generate a unique ID (primary key) via the **unique ID generator**.\n"
                        "5. Convert the ID to `shortURL` with base-62 conversion.\n"
                        "6. Insert a new row with `id, shortURL, longURL`.\n"
                        "\n"
                        "Concrete example: ID `2009215674938` converts to `zn9edcu` (p. 128). The **distributed unique ID generator** produces globally unique IDs — non-trivial in a distributed environment; the book defers it to Chapter 7 (p. 128).\n"
