                        "## Start simple: a single server (p. 248)\n"
                        "\n"
                        "Begin with everything on one box:\n"
                        "- A **web server** to upload/download files.\n"
                        "- A **MySQL database** for metadata (user data, login info, file info).\n"
                        "- A **storage directory** `drive/` (1 TB allocated). Under it sit per-user directories called **namespaces**; each file/folder is uniquely identified by joining the **namespace + relative path** (p. 248).\n"
                        "\n"
                        "## Outgrowing one server\n"
                        "\n"
                        "As uploads pile up the disk fills (the \"space full\" alert). First fix: **shard** the data across multiple storage servers, e.g. sharding by `user_id` (p. 249).\n"
                        "\n"
                        "Sharding solves space but not durability. The chapter moves file storage to **Amazon S3**, an object store offering scalability, availability, security, and performance (p. 250). S3 supports **same-region and cross-region replication**: a **region** is a geographic area with AWS data centers, and a **bucket** is like a folder. Files are **replicated across two separate geographical regions** to guard against data loss (pp. 250-251).\n"
                        "\n"
                        "Further improvements (pp. 250-251):\n"
                        "- **Load balancer** — evenly distributes traffic and redistributes if a web server goes down.\n"
                        "- **Web servers** — now easy to add/remove with load.\n"
                        "- **Metadata DB** — moved off the app server (no single point of failure) with replication + sharding.\n"
                        "- **File storage** — S3, replicated in two regions.\n"
                        "\n"
                        "This **decouples** web servers, the metadata DB, and file storage from the single server.\n"
                        "\n"
                        "## Sync conflicts (pp. 251-252)\n"
                        "\n"
                        "When two users modify the same file at the same time, a conflict occurs. Strategy: **the first version that gets processed wins; the version processed later receives a conflict** (p. 251). In the example, user 1's update goes through and user 2 gets a conflict. The losing client is shown **both copies** — its local copy and the latest server version — and may **merge** them or **override** one with the other (p. 252).\n"
                        "\n"
                        "## High-level components (pp. 253-254)\n"
                        "\n"
                        "- **Block servers** — upload blocks to cloud storage (the heavy lifting of uploads).\n"
                        "- **Cloud storage (S3)** — stores file blocks.\n"
                        "- **Cold storage** — for inactive data not accessed for a long time.\n"
                        "- **Load balancer** — evenly distributes requests across API servers.\n"
                        "- **API servers** — everything except the upload flow: auth, user profiles, metadata updates.\n"
                        "- **Metadata database** — metadata of users, files, blocks, versions (not the files themselves).\n"
                        "- **Metadata cache** — caches hot metadata for fast retrieval.\n"
                        "- **Notification service** — a publisher/subscriber system that tells clients when a file is added/edited/removed elsewhere so they pull the latest.\n"
                        "- **Offline backup queue** — stores changes for offline clients to sync when back online."
